Aggregate Weather Data to provide a consolidated view of daily weather information

In [ ]:
# create function to determine most common values in object columns
def most_common(series):
    return series.value_counts().idxmax()

# group by 'Formatted Date' and aggregate columns
aggregated_weather = weather.groupby('Formatted Date').agg({
    'Summary': most_common,
    'Precip Type': most_common,
    'Temperature (C)': 'mean',
    'Apparent Temperature (C)': 'mean',
    'Humidity': 'mean',
    'Wind Speed (km/h)': 'mean',
    'Wind Bearing (degrees)': 'mean',
    'Visibility (km)': 'mean',
    'Loud Cover': 'mean',
    'Pressure (millibars)': 'mean',
    'Daily Summary': most_common
}).reset_index()

# round numerical values
aggregated_weather = aggregated_weather.round({'Temperature (C)': 0, 'Apparent Temperature (C)': 0, 'Humidity': 2, 'Wind Speed (km/h)': 2, 'Wind Bearing (degrees)': 2, 'Visibility (km)': 0, 'Loud Cover': 2, 'Pressure (millibars)': 0})

# display the aggregated DataFrame
aggregated_weather.head(3)

In [ ]:
# Creating animation
import matplotlib.animation as animation
from matplotlib.animation import FuncAnimation

# set the size, axis and the labels for the frame
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
ax = plt.axes(xlim=(2006,2016), ylim=(-20,35))
line, = ax.plot([], [], lw=1, color='orange')
ax.set_xlabel('Year')
ax.set_ylabel('Temperature (C)')
ax.set_title('Temperature Time Series')

# rotate x-axis labels for better readability
plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')

# function to initialize the animation
def init():
    line.set_data([], [])
    return line,

# function to update the animation for each frame
def update(num, line):
    # update the y-data of the line with the 'Temperature (C)' column from aggregated_weather
    y_data = aggregated_weather['Temperature (C)'].iloc[:num].values
    line.set_ydata(y_data)
    return line,

# generate x values for the time range
x = np.linspace(2006,2016,3650) 

# function to animate the temperature time series
def animate(i):
    # update the y-data of the line with the 'Temperature (C)' column from aggregated_weather
    y_data = aggregated_weather['Temperature (C)'].iloc[:i].values
    line.set_ydata(y_data)

    # ensure that the lengths of x and y_data match
    line.set_xdata(x[:len(y_data)])

    # add grid to the plot
    ax.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)
    return line,

# create the animation
anim1 = animation.FuncAnimation(fig, animate,
                               init_func=init,
                               frames=3650,
                               interval=20,
                               blit=True)

# draw the plot
plt.draw()

# save the animation as an MP4 video file
anim1.save('temperature.mp4', writer = 'ffmpeg', fps = 65)

# Creating animation
from matplotlib.ticker import MultipleLocator

# set the size, axis and the labels for the frame
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
ax = plt.axes(xlim=(2006, 2008), ylim=(-20, 35))
line1, = ax.plot([], [], lw=3, label='Temperature (C)', color='blue')
line2, = ax.plot([], [], lw=1, label='Apparent Temperature (C)', color='red')
ax.set_xlabel('Time')
ax.set_ylabel('Temperature (C)')
ax.set_title('Difference between temperature and apparent temperature')

# rotate x-axis labels for better readability
plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')

# function to initialize the animation
def init():
    line1.set_data([], [])
    line2.set_data([], [])
    return line1, line2

# function to update the animation for each frame
def update(num, line1, line2, data):
    # NOTE_: data parameter (or any variable name) could be used as placeholder for the current DataFrame 
    # update the y-data of the lines with the 'Temperature (C)' and 'Apparent Temperature (C)' columns from aggregated_weather
    y_data_temp = data['Temperature (C)'].iloc[:num].values
    y_data_apparent_temp = data['Apparent Temperature (C)'].iloc[:num].values

    line1.set_ydata(y_data_temp)
    line2.set_ydata(y_data_apparent_temp)

    return line1, line2

# generate x values for the time range
x = np.linspace(2006, 2008, 730)

# function to animate the temperature time series
def animate(i):
    # Update the y-data of the lines with the 'Temperature (C)' and 'Apparent Temperature (C)' columns from aggregated_weather
    y_data_temp = aggregated_weather['Temperature (C)'].iloc[:i].values
    y_data_apparent_temp = aggregated_weather['Apparent Temperature (C)'].iloc[:i].values

    line1.set_ydata(y_data_temp)
    line2.set_ydata(y_data_apparent_temp)

    # ensure that the lengths of x and y_data match
    line1.set_xdata(x[:len(y_data_temp)])
    line2.set_xdata(x[:len(y_data_apparent_temp)])

    # add grid to the plot
    ax.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)
    
    return line1, line2

# create the animation
anim2 = animation.FuncAnimation(fig, animate,
                               init_func=init,
                               frames=730,
                               interval=20,
                               blit=True)

# draw the plot
plt.draw()
# save the animation as an MP4 video file
anim2.save('temp_difference.mp4', writer='ffmpeg', fps=30)

# extract the year from the 'Formatted Date' column
aggregated_weather['Year'] = aggregated_weather['Formatted Date'].dt.year

# create a dictionary of DataFrames, where each key is a year
yearly_data = {}

# iterate over unique years and create separate DataFrames
for year in aggregated_weather['Year'].unique():
    yearly_data[year] = aggregated_weather[aggregated_weather['Year'] == year].copy()

# access DataFrame for the years 2006-2016

data_2007 = yearly_data[2007]

# set the size, axis and the labels for the frame
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
ax = plt.axes(xlim=(2012,2013), ylim=(1,35))
line, = ax.plot([], [], lw=1, color='violet')
ax.set_xlabel('Year 2012')
ax.set_ylabel('Wind Speed (km/h)')
ax.set_title('Wind speed through the year')

# function to initialize the animation
def init():
    line.set_data([], [])
    return line,

# function to update the animation for each frame
def update(num, line, data):
    # update the y-data of the line with the 'Temperature (C)' column from aggregated_weather
    y_data = aggregated_weather['Wind Speed (km/h)'].iloc[:num].values
    line.set_ydata(y_data)

    return line,

# generate x values for the time range
x = np.linspace(2012,2013,365) 

# function to animate the temperature time series
def animate(i):
    # update the y-data of the line with the 'Temperature (C)' column from aggregated_weather
    y_data = aggregated_weather['Wind Speed (km/h)'].iloc[:i].values
    line.set_ydata(y_data)

    # ensure that the lengths of x and y_data match
    line.set_xdata(x[:len(y_data)])

    # set major locator to position grid
    ax.xaxis.set_major_locator(MultipleLocator(base=1))

    return line,

# create the animation

                               init_func=init,
                               frames=365,
                               interval=20,
                               blit=True)

# draw the plot

# save the animation as an MP4 video file
anim3.save('wind.mp4', writer = 'ffmpeg', fps = 50)

In Conclusion:¶

This project highlights the use of animated visualizations to present time series data, using weather patterns as an example. The animations effectively showcase changes in temperature, wind, and humidity over time, demonstrating a clear and engaging method to visualize data trends. This approach underlines the potential of animation to make complex data easily understandable and visually appealing.
